<br>
There's a huge difference.  <br>
<br>
For instance, in Drack's post, he uses the word &quot;epitamy.&quot;  Now, I *know* he means to say &quot;epitome,&quot; and I know he knows what the word means, so there's no point in correcting him here.  However, if he were coming at me here like, say, Estephe seems to revel in doing, I'd be all over him like white on rice, because, like it or not, it's a sign of weakness, and in a rant forum, weakness=death.  However, I'm guessing that, based on my half-a$$ed psychological profile of Drack's personality, he'll probably read this and commit the proper spelling to memory, because he's not stupid, and doesn't like being perceived as such.  I could absolutely be off-base, but I doubt it.  <br>
<br>
Here's another example...for the longest time I thought the latin expression &quot;ad hominem&quot; was spelled &quot;ad homonym.&quot;  A simple mistake, and certainly an esoteric phrase, but still one that I was ignorant of--UNTIL someone corrected me.  I've never made it since, and regardless of what their intention may have been, I'm *glad* that they set me straight, because there's just no way to convince me that being ignorant is somehow &quot;cool.&quot;  <br>
<br>
If being corrected for improper grammar makes you so upset that you fume about it in a Rants forum, then maybe you should consider taking the corrections to heart.  I hate to sound like some contrite motivational speaker, but knowledge really is power, kids. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#628CBC>- </font><a href=http://pub169.ezboard.com/bmtboards>Morell-Thule Forums</a><font color=#628CBC> - </font><a href=http://pub169.ezboard.com/fmtboardsfrm3>Rants</a> <font color=#628CBC> - </font><a href="http://sevendragons.net">Morell-Thule Community Website</a><font color=#628CBC> - </font> <center><form name=f>Select Message Board:<br>
